'''James Wood Bush''' ({{circa|1844}} – April 24, 1906) was an American [[Union Navy]] sailor of [[British people|British]] and [[Native Hawaiians|Native Hawaiian]] descent. One of the "Hawaiʻi Sons of the Civil War", he was among a group of more than one hundred documented Native Hawaiian and Hawaii-born combatants who fought in the [[American Civil War]] while the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]] was still an independent nation. 

Enlisting in the Union Navy in 1864, he served as sailor aboard the [[USS Vandalia (1828)|USS ''Vandalia'']] and the captured Confederate vessel [[USS Beauregard (1861)|USS ''Beauregard'']], maintaining the [[Union blockade|blockade]] of the ports of the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]]. He was discharged from service in 1865 after receiving an injury, which developed into a chronic condition in later life. Unable to immediately return home, the impoverished Bush took more than a decade to return to Hawaii, journeying through [[New England]] and much of the Pacific. Back in Hawaii, he worked as a government tax collector and road supervisor for the island of [[Kauai]], where he settled down. In later life he converted to [[Mormonism]] and became an active member of the [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Hawaii|Hawaiian Mission]]. After the annexation of Hawaii to the United States, Bush was recognized for his service and granted a government pension in 1905 for the injuries he received in the Navy. He died at his home on Kauai, on April 24, 1906.

For a period of time after the end of the war, the legacy and contributions of Bush and other documented Hawaiian participants in the American Civil War were largely forgotten except in the private circles of descendants and historians. However, there has been a revival of interest in recent years, especially through the work and efforts of his great grandniece Edna Bush Ellis and others in the Hawaiian community. In 2010, the "Hawaiʻi Sons of the Civil War" were commemorated with a bronze plaque erected along the memorial pathway at the [[National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific]] in Honolulu.

==Early life ==
[[File:John E. Bush.jpg|right|120px|thumb|Brother [[John E. Bush]] <!-- was influential in Hawaiian politics -->]]
James Wood Bush was born in [[Honolulu]]. The date of his birth is uncertain; different sources claim it to be October 1844,{{sfn|Taylor|1906a|page=359}}{{sfn|Taylor|1906b|page=827}} 1845,{{sfn|Vance|Manning|2015b|page=158}}<ref name="Vance&Manning2012"/> or 1847–48.<ref name="DeathPCA"/>
He was the son of George Henry Bush (1807–1853), a native of [[Suffolk|Suffolk, England,]] who went to Hawaii in 1825, and his Hawaiian wife.<ref name="FatherGrave">{{cite sign|title=Grave Marker of George Henry Bush|type=|location=Honolulu, Hawaii|institution=[[Oahu Cemetery]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sale By Order of the Supreme Court|newspaper=The Polynesian|location=Honolulu|date=March 21, 1863|volume=XIX|issue=47|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1863-03-21/ed-1/seq-3/}}</ref>
Bush was thus of mixed [[native Hawaiian]] and [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]] descent, known as ''[[hapa|hapa haole]]'' in [[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]], although in his lifetime he was referred to as a "[[half-caste]]".{{sfn|Jenson|1895|pages=524–525}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Punaboy|title=Hawai’i Sons of the Civil War|website=Aloha Valley|date=June 20, 2015|url=http://alohavalley.com/hawaii-sons-of-the-civil-war/|accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> His older brother was [[John E. Bush|John Edward Bush]], who became a newspaper publisher and politician, serving as [[Governors of Kauai|royal governor of Kauaʻi]] and a cabinet minister under the reign of King [[Kalākaua]].<ref name="DeathPCA"/><ref name="office">{{cite web|url=http://archives1.dags.hawaii.gov/gsdl/collect/governme/index/assoc/HASH6390.dir/Bush,%20John%20Edward.jpg|title=Bush, John Edward office record|work=State archives digital collections|publisher=state of Hawaii|accessdate=October 22, 2010}}</ref> Little is known about Bush's life before 1864. Like his brother, he began his career as a sailor working on either merchant or whaling ships in the Pacific.{{sfn|Vance|Manning|2015b|page=158}} Hawaiian sailors were highly regarded in the 18th- and 19th-century maritime industry.{{sfn|Manning|2013|page=87}}

==American Civil War==
After the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]], the [[Kingdom of Hawaii|Kingdom of Hawaiʻi]] under King [[Kamehameha IV]] declared its neutrality on August&nbsp;26, 1861.{{sfn|Kuykendall|1953|pages=57–66}} But many [[Native Hawaiian]]s and Hawaiian-born Americans (mainly descendants of the American missionaries) both abroad and in the islands volunteered and enlisted in the military regiments of various states in the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] and the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]].{{sfn|Grzyb|2016|pages=127–128}}<ref name="Damon1941">{{cite news|last=Damon|first=Ethel M.|title=Punahou Volunteers of 1863|newspaper=The Friend|location=Honolulu|publisher=|date=April 1, 1941|volume=CXI|issue=4|page=67|url=http://server.honstudios.com/mhm-friend/cgi-bin/mhm-friend?a=d&d=Friend19410401-01.2.5&cl|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> Individual Native Hawaiians had been serving in the United States Navy and Army since the [[War of 1812]], and even more served during the American Civil War.{{sfn|Schmitt|1998|pages=171–172}} Many Hawaiians sympathized with the Union because of Hawaiʻi's ties to [[New England]] through its missionaries and the whaling industries, and the ideological opposition of many to the institution of [[Slavery in the United States|slavery]].{{sfn|Manning|Vance|2014|pages=145–170}}{{sfn|Vance|Manning|2015a|pages=132–135}}

[[File:USS Vandalia (1828) sketch.jpg|right|thumb|Bush served as a sailor on the [[USS Vandalia (1828)|USS ''Vandalia'']] during the war.]]
Arriving in New England at the beginning of the war, Bush enlisted at [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire|Portsmouth]], [[New Hampshire]] as an "Ordinary Seaman" on September 27, 1864. During his service, he worked on the [[USS Vandalia (1828)|USS ''Vandalia'']] and later the captured Confederate vessel [[USS Beauregard (1861)|USS ''Beauregard'']], chasing [[blockade runner]]s off West Florida, as part of the [[Atlantic Blockading Squadron|Blockading Squadrons]] responsible for maintaining the [[Union blockade|blockade]] of the ports of the Confederacy. He developed chronic laryngitis and spinal injuries due to his service in the Union Navy and was discharged in September 1865 at the Brooklyn Naval Hospital. After the war ended, the impoverished Bush had no way of returning to Hawaii. For the next decade, he lived in [[New Bedford]], [[San Francisco]], and [[Tahiti]], finally returning to Hawaii in 1877.{{sfn|Vance|Manning|2015b|page=158}}<ref name="Vance&Manning2012">{{cite journal|last1=Vance|first1=Justin W.|last2=Manning|first2=Anita|title=The Effects of the American Civil War on Hawai'i and the Pacific World|journal=World History Connected|volume=9|issue=3|year=October 2012|location=|publisher=University of Illinois|url=http://worldhistoryconnected.press.illinois.edu/9.3/vance.html|pages=}}</ref><ref name="Foenander">{{cite web|last1=Foenander|first1=Terry|last2=Milligan|first2=Edward|display-authors=etal|title=Hawaiians in the Civil War|date=March 2015|url=http://www.nps.gov/civilwar/upload/More-Info-on-Hawaiians-in-the-Civil-War-Alphabetically-by-Name.pdf|work=National Park Service|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> In 1905, after Hawaii become a US territory, Bush was granted a pension for his service in the Civil War, with back pensions dating from May 8, 1897.{{sfn|Shively|2015|pages=158, 170}}<ref name="PensionPCA">{{cite news|title=Local Brevities|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=June 18, 1905|volume=III|issue=129|page=12|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1905-06-18/ed-1/seq-12/}}</ref><ref name="PensionHStar">{{cite news|title=Gets Pension|newspaper=The Hawaiian Star|location=Honolulu|date=June 19, 1905|volume=XIII|issue=4132|page=2|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015415/1905-06-19/ed-1/seq-2/}}</ref>

==Later life==
After returning to Hawaii, Bush settled on the island of [[Kauai]]. In 1880, he was listed as the tax collector of Kawaihau, Kauai.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tax Collectors for 1880|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=September 4, 1880|volume=XXV|issue=10|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015418/1880-09-04/ed-1/seq-3/}}</ref> In 1882, his older brother in his capacity as Minister of Interior appointed him Road Supervisor for the District of Hanalei to replace Christian Bertlemann, who had resigned.<ref>{{cite news|title=Message from the Interior Office|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=September 30, 1882|volume=XXVII|issue=14|page=2|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015418/1882-09-30/ed-1/seq-2/}}</ref> In 1887, Bush converted to [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Hawaii|Mormonism]] and was ordained an elder after two years; he took an active part in missionary work in the islands. He became the [[Bishop (Latter Day Saints)|bishop]] of the Latter-day Saints [[Ward (LDS Church)|ward]] in Kealia and hosted LDS historian [[Andrew Jenson]] during his 1895 visit to Kauai.{{sfn|Jenson|1895|pages=524–525}}{{sfn|Taylor|1906a|page=359}}{{sfn|Taylor|1906b|page=827}} In around 1894, Bush married a young girl at [[Lahaina]], traveling to [[Kona District, Hawaii|Kona]] after their marriage.<ref name="MarriagePCA">{{cite news|title=Local Brevities|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=November 21, 1894|volume=XX|issue=3848|page=7|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1894-11-21/ed-1/seq-7/}}</ref>

[[File:Hawaiian Veteran of Civil War Dies, 1906.jpg|thumb|right|"Hawaiian Veteran of Civil War Dies", Bush's death announcement in ''The Pacific Commercial Advertiser'', 1906]]
Bush died of [[heart failure]] at [[Kealia, Hawaii|Kealia]], Kauai, on April 24, 1906. In the last years of his life, he was a janitor at the Kealia prison. Bush was survived by his wife and son.<ref name="DeathPCA">{{cite news|title=Hawaiian Veteran of Civil War Dies|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=April 26, 1906|volume=XLIII|issue=7399|page=11|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1906-04-26/ed-1/seq-11/}}</ref> Lorenzo Taylor, writing for the ''[[Deseret News]]'', shortly after Bush's death,  said, "[H]e has taken an active part in the missionary work, doing much good among his fellow men. He has also been very kind to the elders, and his doors were always open to them. He was greatly beloved and respected by all who knew him. His life was a noble example of faithful and untiring devotion to the Gospel."{{sfn|Taylor|1906a|page=359}}{{sfn|Taylor|1906b|page=827}} Bush was believed to be buried on Kauai, but the location of his grave is uncertain. According to Anita Manning, an Associate in Cultural Studies at [[Bishop Museum]], "even the family can't find him".<ref name="Cole2014">{{cite news|last=Cole|first=William|title=Civil War Veteran's Grave Will Remain Unmarked|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-3227159071.html|date=February 23, 2014|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|location=Honolulu}}</ref>

==Legacy==
After the war, the military service of Hawaiians, including James Wood Bush and many others, was largely forgotten, disappearing from the collective memories of the American Civil War and the history of Hawaii. However, in recent years, Hawaiian residents, historians, and descendants of Hawaiian combatants in the conflict have insisted on the need to remember the legacy of the Hawaiians who fought. Renewed interest in the stories of these individuals and this particular period of Hawaiian-American history have inspired efforts to preserve the memories of the Hawaiians who served in the war.{{sfn|Vance|Manning|2015c|pages=161–163}}

[[File:Honolulu-memorial-Hawaiisonsofthecivilwar.JPG|thumb|Memorial plaque for Hawai‘i Sons of the Civil War in the [[National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific]], Honolulu]]
Stating "our boys from Hawaii" should be remembered, Bush's great-grandniece Edna Bush Ellis was influential in reviving interest and the effort to install a memorial recognizing their legacy.{{sfn|Vance|Manning|2015c|pages=161–163}}<ref name="Burlingame2008">{{cite web|last=Burlingame|first=Burl|title=Reviving History|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|date=August 26, 2008|location=Honolulu|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/26/features/story01.html}}</ref> On August&nbsp;26, 2010, on the anniversary of the signing of the Hawaiian Neutrality Proclamation, a bronze plaque was erected along the memorial pathway at the [[National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific]] in Honolulu recognizing the "Hawaiʻi Sons of the Civil War", the more than one hundred documented Hawaiians who served during the American Civil War for both the Union and the Confederacy.{{sfn|Vance|Manning|2015c|pages=161–163}}<ref name="Cole2010">{{cite news|last=Cole|first=William|title=Native Hawaiians served on both sides during Civil War|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/May/31/ln/hawaii5310346.html|date=May 31, 2010|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|location=Honolulu}}</ref><ref name="Plaque">{{cite web|title=Memorial Plaque|website=Hawaiʻi Sons of the Civil War|url=http://hawaiisonsofthecivilwar.com/memorial-plaque/|accessdate=June 5, 2016}}</ref>
As of 2014, researchers have identified 119 documented Native Hawaiian and Hawaii-born combatants from historical records. The exact number still remains unclear because many Hawaiians enlisted and served under Anglicized names, and little is known about them due to the lack of detailed records.{{sfn|Grzyb|2016|pages=127–128}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Chelsea|title=Hawaiian Civil War soldier finally recognized|newspaper=Hawaii News Show|date=October 26, 2014|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/27016661/hawaiian-civil-war-solider-finally-recognized}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Punaboy|title=Hawaiʻi Sons of the Civil War|website=Aloha Valley|date=June 20, 2015|url=http://alohavalley.com/hawaii-sons-of-the-civil-war/|accessdate=June 5, 2016}}</ref>

In 2015, the sesquicentennial of the end of the American Civil War, the [[National Park Service]] released a publication, entitled ''Asians and Pacific Islanders and the Civil War'', about the service of the large number of combatants of Asian and Pacific Islander descent who fought during the war. The history of Hawaii's involvement and the biographies of Bush and others were written by historians Anita Manning, Justin Vance and others.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hawaiʻi Pacific University|title=HPU partners with National Park Service, Hawaii Civil War Round Table for July 17 talk|newspaper=HPU News|date=July 15, 2015|url=http://www.hpu.edu/HPUNews/2015/07/civil-war.html}}</ref>{{sfn|Shively|2015|pages=130–163}}

